'''José Manuel Bento dos Santos''' (born 1947) is a Portuguese [[cook (profession)|cook]], [[gastronomer]], businessman, [[trader (finance)|trader]], metals broker, writer and [[chemical engineer]]. Bento dos Santos studied chemical-industrial engineering at the [[Instituto Superior Técnico]] (IST), [[Technical University of Lisbon]]. During his early university years he played [[rugby union]] and was also the manager of the [[Portugal national rugby union team|Portugal national rugby team]] in 1967/1968. He started his professional career as an employee of [[Companhia União Fabril]] (CUF), the largest Portuguese business [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] before the [[Carnation Revolution]] in 1974. During the turmoil of the revolution, indeed a left-wing military coup, CUF was forcibly [[nationalized]] by the revolutionary government and collapsed. Bento dos Santos, together with other partners such as [[Eduardo Catroga]], founded the metals brokerage and trading company Quimibro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europages.pt/QUIMIBRO-METAIS-E-MINERAIS-LDA/bch-EUR-PRT031497-00101-25-xx/informacoes-sobre-a-empresa.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325191629/http://www.europages.pt/QUIMIBRO-METAIS-E-MINERAIS-LDA/bch-EUR-PRT031497-00101-25-xx/informacoes-sobre-a-empresa.html |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df= }} QUIMIBRO – METAIS E MINERAIS, LDA</ref><ref>http://www.portugalio.com/quimibro-metais-e-minerais/ Quimibro – Metais e Minerais, Lda</ref> In the late 1980s, [[Pedro Passos Coelho]], future Prime Minister of Portugal, was invited by a cousin to work there as a collaborator. Bento dos Santos studied also economics at the ''Instituto Superior de Economia e Gestão'' of the [[Technical University of Lisbon]], but he did not graduate.<ref>{{pt icon}} [http://www.josedemello.pt/gjm_press_05.asp?lang=pt&empresa=18&noticia=7142 José Bento dos Santos], [[Grupo José de Mello]]</ref> Beyond Quimibro, Bento dos Santos founded other ventures like Quinta do Monte d'Oiro,<ref>http://www.quintadomontedoiro.com/</ref> a [[winery]]. In the 2000s, Bento dos Santos became popular due to his [[cuisine]] progames ''O Sentido do Gosto'' (2007) on the Portuguese television [[Rádio e Televisão de Portugal|RTP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww1.rtp.pt/wportal/sites/tv/sentidodogosto/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-06-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314101339/http://ww1.rtp.pt/wportal/sites/tv/sentidodogosto/ |archivedate=14 March 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.mandala.pt/sentidodogosto/default_receitas.htm</ref> and ''Segredos do Vinho'' ([[Sociedade Independente de Comunicação|SIC]], 2004).  He also published a book of cuisine with the title ''O Sentido do Gosto''<ref>http://www.wook.pt/ficha/o-sentido-do-gosto/a/id/224999</ref> as well as ''Subtilezas Gastronómicas – receitas à volta de um vinho'' (Assírio & Alvim, 2005). He is affiliated with the International Gastronomy Academy, the [[Confrérie de la Chaîne des Rôtisseurs]], the Confraria do [[Vinho do Porto]], the Académie des Psycologues du Goût, and is a ''chevalier'' of both ''des Entonneurs Rabelaisiens'' and ''du [[Tastevin]]''.

